ðŸ“˜ Var-Args in Java

Concept

Introduced in JDK 1.5
Stands for Variable Arguments, allowing a method to accept 0 or more parameters.
Represented using ...
Can hold heterogeneous types using Object type.
Must be the last parameter in method.

Extra Point:
Var-args internally behaves like an array, so you can loop through values easily.

Valid & Invalid Var-Args Rules

âŒ Invalid examples:

public void accept(float... x, int... y) {} // multiple var-args not allowed
public void accept(int... x, int y) {} // var-args must be last
public void accept(int... x, int... y) {} // only one var-args allowed

âœ” Valid example:

class Sample {
    public void accept(int x, int... y) {
        System.out.println("x value is: " + x);
        for (int z : y) {
            System.out.println(z);
        }
    }
}

public class VarArgsDemo4 {
    public static void main(String... args) {
        Sample s1 = new Sample();
        s1.accept(12, 10, 20, 30, 40, 50);
    }
}

You must give at least one main item, then additional items can be any number.

