ðŸ“˜ Method Overriding in Java

Concept

Method Overriding â†’ Runtime (Dynamic) Polymorphism

Redefining superclass non-static method in subclass with:
1 > Same method name
2 > Same parameters (method signature)
3 > Compatible return type (Co-variant allowed)

Static methods â†’ Method Hiding (Not overriding)

âœ” Example of Overriding
class Super {
    public void m1() {
    }
}

class Sub extends Super {
    public void m1() {   // Overridden method
        // New Implementation
    }
}

Advantage of Method Overriding
Allows subclass to provide its own behavior.
Example:

class Animal {
    public void eat() {
        System.out.println("Generic Eating");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    public void eat() {
        System.out.println("Non Veg type");
    }
}

class Horse extends Animal {
    public void eat() {
        System.out.println("Veg Type");
    }
}

